public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 0) {
            return false; // 0 is not a power of 3
        } else if (n == 0) {
            return false; // 0 is not a power of 3
        } else if (n == 1) {
            return false; // 1 is not a power of 3
        } else if (n == 2) {
            return true; // 2 is a power of 3
        }

        // check if n is a power of 3
        int mask = 2;
        while (mask < n) {
            if ((n & mask)!= 0) {
                return false; // n is not a power of 3
            }
            mask <<= 1;
        }

        return true; // n is a power of 3
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
    }
}
```
In this solution, we first check if the input number is negative, zero, or one. If it is, we return false immediately.

Next, we use a bitwise AND operation to check if the input number is a power of three. We use a mask of 2 and shift it left until it covers all the bits of the input number. If any bit of the result of the AND operation is non-zero, then the input number is not a power of three and we return false. Otherwise, the input number is a power of three and we return true.

